1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 (4. Nf3 Bg4 { [%cal Ge5d6,Gc7d6] } 5. Be2 c6!? { The so-called Flohr variation } 6. O-O Bxf3 7. Bxf3 dxe5 8. dxe5 e6 9. c4?! (9. Qe2 { and }) (9. Nd2 { are considered improvements and are probably slightly more comfortable for White. }) 9... Ne7! { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7g6,Gg6e5] } 10. Qxd8+? (10. Qe2! { is no doubt stronger. }) 10... Kxd8 { and it's actually quite difficult to defend the e-pawn. } { Kaidanov, Gregory S - Ivanchuk, Vassily, 0-1, URS-ch FL55, 1987, https://lichess.org/6bOksFXe } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7g6,Gg6e5,Gb8d7,Yf8b4,Yb4a5,Ya5c7] }) (4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 (5. exd6 cxd6) 5... g6 6. Nc3 dxe5 7. fxe5 c5 8. d5 { [%csl Ge5] } 8... Bg7 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Nf3?! (10. Qd2! { is much stronger }) 10... Bg4! 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 N8d7 { [%csl Ge5] } 13. Qe3 Qb8! 14. e6 Ne5 15. exf7+? Rxf7 { [%cal Gf7f4] } 16. Bh2 Nexc4! 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Qxc5 Qc8 (18... Nxb2! 19. Bxb8 Nd3+ $19) 19. Qxc8+ Rxc8 { Panarin, Michail - Polaczek, Richard, 1/2-1/2, Champions Challenge 106th, 2005, https://lichess.org/RrKWUCcO }) 4... cxd6 5. c4 Nb6 { Black has secured an extra central pawn, which can result in a structure later where only Black has an e-pawn. This can result in structures later where Black builds up a large center with f5+e5 and dominates in the center. This can have long-reaching consequences, even into the ending. See the following chapters on the power of an e-pawn. } { [%cal Ge7e5,Bd6d5] } 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Nf3?! { [%csl Gf3] } (8. Rc1! { is the "dreaded" Voronezh variation } 8... O-O 9. b3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. c5 N6d7 13. Bc4 Nc6 14. Nf3 h6 15. Ne4 Na5 16. Be2 f5 $10 { Seelig, Jürgen - Schmidt, Loren R., 1/2-1/2, VWC11/SF  9, 2020, https://lichess.org/sZezhnLH } { [%csl Gf5,Ge5] }) 8... O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bg4 11. b3 d5! 12. c5 Nc8 13. h3?! Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 $15 { and it's very hard to defend the d4-pawn. } { Aigner, Michael - Nakamura, Hikaru, 0-1, North American op 17th, 2007, https://lichess.org/QIVtm7RS } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc8e7,Ge7f5,Yd8f6] } *


